name: COL
comment: (THYME) TOI-450, Columba association. Tokovinin already acquired speckle images.  Being pursued by E. Newton & team for RV cluster membership confirmation. Proprietary HARPS specturm in F. Bouchy's hands. SALT/HRS (2), Gemini/IGRINS (2020A)        SALT/HRS, Gemini/IGRINS, THYME Collaboration (Tofflemire). Ziegler did contrast curve. --> IS EB (ANDREW MANN, PRIV COMM.)

name: PscEri
comment: TOI-451, Psc-Eri. Zhou/Quinn's CHIRON spectrum shows Li absorption. Ziegler did contrast curve. Has total of THREE PCs on ExoFOPTESS. Spectrum shows vsini=9km/s --> Prot = 5, not 2.5days.

name: Pozzo_1,Vela_OB2,cg19velaOB2_pop7,N/A,Pozzo_1,Vela_OB2,cg19velaOB2_pop7,N/A
comment: LCOGT(1, non-detection b/c bad epoch; 1 OIBEO 20191216 reduced, but ruined by clouds). "3 GAIA stars within 5" SG1 finds tentative detection in aperture including target and two nearby stars.". SG2 flags as CPC-. Nbhd analysis shows parallax good, pm both viable. Pretty dispersed cluster (few deg) and far from core in ra/dec... and star is on UMS. Needs spectroscopy. Ziegler did contrast -curve.

name: Trumpler_10,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop2,Trumpler_10,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop2
comment: LCOGT (1, non-detection b/c bad epoch, 1 pending JH reduc 20200101). "SG1 clears many stars of NEB, but a handful of potential contami--ts remain. Will try again." SG1 flags as PPC. Parallax good, PM probably within like 1 sigma of cluster PM dispersion. Spatially also medium distance from core (not too far, not too close). Ziegler did contrast curve. Rp=4.7Re. P=1.4d. d=400pc. (Eastman). Rstar=1.7Rsun, Teff~=11000K. Sector8+9 data are available. LC might show extra PCs?

name: IC_2602,IC_2602,IC_2602,IC2602
comment: FEROS (4). Has Li. LC shows strong rot signal (2% amplitude). LCOGT 1 OIB (non-det, bad epoch). Multisector available. SG1 flagged as single transit -- but now it's NOT (P=8days). Despite Gaia & CG18 membership, nbhd analysis shows parallax is nearly 0.25mas larger than typical in cluster -- possibility of foreground star (star isn't particularly bright/blue, no offset argument). PMs are good. Positions are decent. RV is good. P=8d, Rp=8Re. vsini=17km/s observed from FEROS. single-lined early-G/late-F type star. Li EW is consistent with a young star (more so than a typical field Teff=6100K G dwarf). Ziegler did contrast curve, compnaion (deltaI=4.5) at ~2.1 arcsec introduces NEB blend scenario. Gaia DR2 info of the companion strongly suggests it's bound (same PMs and parallax). There's also a DeltaT=3 star at 5 arcsec, possible blend.

name: NGC_2516,NGC_2516,--,NGC_2516,NGC_2516,--
comment: "Crowded field". TIC 372913430. 0.5% dip, P=13.5 days, Teff=9100K. RA/dec in center of cluster, parallax good as well. PMs are surprisingly far from PM of cluster center (>1, maybe 2 sigma). Given the position & parallax, likely not an issue. (RV might clarify?). Ziegler got speckle AO, rules out binary companion to ~0.2-0.3 arcsec.

name: Platais_5,--,Platais_5,--
comment: SG1 clears field of NEBs, though crowded. vsini=120km/s (CHIRON, Zhou); NRES fast rotator too. Rp=2.0Re, P=0.52d (Eastman). PM of ~10mas/yr in each dirn, d=200pc. NB. Platais 5 moving group is young enough that the KC19 HR diagram shows the PMS for the M dwarfs -- the HRD is awesome. The velocity string is also clear. (CG18 did not report Platais 5, but not surprising b/c of how sparse it is). Nbhd analysis from K13 "members" suggestive but not convincing. FROM K13: ----Plx vs pmdec shows an overdensity, suggesting the group is real. The CMD looks decent. RA/dec not at all convincing. (But note KC19 maybe better for this one...)----- FROM KC19: The neighborhood assessment looks pretty convincing. The RV for this star is where it should be. Two big clumps, PM is right on. Quinn got 2 RVs w/ CHIRON. Ziegler did contrast curve, rules out binary companion to within dM=5 at 1arcsec (~200AU b/c d=200pc), similar down to ~50AU.

name: AB_Dor,--,AB_Dor,--
pending_photometry_observations: ephemeris too imprecise. eastman's 1 sigma uncertainty is 0.5 days
comment: "Period is double or four times larger; T0=1481". P~40day. TIC 130415266. Two transits viewed... ! Teff~9600K, T=7.6. Tricky to schedule (for transit followup). HD 52470. Nothing on the HARPS archive. An RV to place it in the strong AB Dor RV stream (or not) would be helpful. In v_l vs longitude (mw2d plot), clearly apparent stream. In the nbhd plots, it's not obvious (but maybe this is a projection problem?) Ziegler did contrast curve.

name: Platais_5,--,Platais_5,--
pending_photometry_observations: Need with a <1m telescope(?), though 2mmag is hard. No good comparison stars.
comment: LCOGT (1, 20191224. 10 mmag precision, no chance for a 3 mmag transit. Not enough comparison stars – was experimental at 2 sec exposure. Result of experiment was: for LCO 1m, bright limit is like V=8.5). "Might be diluted; SG1 to check". From K13 members, not at all convincing. From KC19 members, PM and parallax plausible for it being a member of the stream. NEED AN RV TO CHECK. And spectra to determine youth. NB. independently found this one from CDIPS in Sector 6 -- threw it out b/c was "just ZariUMS PC". But the dips look weirdly close to being in phase w/ some kind of stellar pulsation mode (only every ~4 or 6 oscillations?!). Ziegler got speckle AO, shows binary companion at 2.11arcsec, deltaI=1.3mag. Note TOI 1014 == TIC 96246348 on exoFOP-TESS but this is wrong, it’s TIC 772008799

name: kc19group_237,--,kc19group_237,--
comment: LCOGT (1, no detection, but consistent w/ shallow depth). "need SG1 to check 400595381; likely BEB". Group is somewhat weak. A bit too old for PMS to be super-convincing (but maybe other indicators possible). Star membership in group from nbhd plot looks pretty good. (Though the group membership is not much stronger).

name: kc19group_64
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SQ 2 CHIRON pending. Need 1 recon spectrum. Should see strong Li. Then need 3 RVs to assess mass measurement prospects (Rp=2.5Re, spot amplitude could be larger than planet signal). Validation paper is worthwhile if mass measurement will require many seasons.
comment: "bright potential L1 candidate". QLP shows ~0.5-1% strong rotational variability (as-in, strong young star). The PMS of the group looks good. Star has plx of ~12.5mas, compared to group mean of ~9.8 pm 1mas. Nbhd analysis shows the group is definitely real. Like it's a freakin whopper. Young enough that spectra (Li, Halpha,..) will clarify youth. Worth pursuing. Mann weakly suggests a secondary eclipse.
LCOGT(1, ambiguous). Many HATS(good). Possible PMS dwarf with close-in giant planet (else EB). ~4% amplitude spot signal. T~=15 and red, so maybe best for a NIR spectrograph?

name: NGC_2323
comment: KeplerCam photometry (Allyson Bieryla) shows it's a NEB. Was labelled Giant PC in M50, ~100Myr star with rotational variability. CHIRON (2, Zhou), showed star has double-peaked CCF, large RV variation. RV=24km/s and RV=128 km/s measured.
Possible HJ around PMS star. Main worry is stellar-mass EB (and rotation period seems to be near the orbital period).

name: NGC_2516,NGC_2516,NGC2516,NGC_2516
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SQ 1 CHIRON pending, recon for RV to confirm NGC 2516 membership. (+Stellar params).
comment: LCOGT(2, 1 BEO i' good, 1 OIBE in g' with depth comparable to i'). 1 SG1 (Phil Evans, IBE, successful).  P~12 day WJ, NGC 2516. Multiple sector data available-> would benefit from multi-sector analysis. Gaia-DR2 RV in tension with Soubiran cluster RV, but at low significance -- higher precision RV requested. Otherwise nbhd analysis is good (plx, proper motion, positions all fine).  Ziegler got speckle AO, shows faint double-dot to NE/SW of the ACF at sep 1arcsec -- but Ziegler says is spurious (would be deltamag 4.). d=400pc.  Rstar=1.35, Teff=6150K (TICv8).

name: Alessi_3,Alessi_3,--,Alessi_3,Alessi_3,--
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SQ 1 CHIRON pending. (1 CHIRON done from GZ)
comment: Priority for RVs. Cand super neptune. LCOGT(2 done, 2 pending reduc 20191229 gp, 20200107 gp), 1 CHAT (i-band), OIBE/IBEO. All 3 reduced transits are good.  CHIRON(1 recon, GZ email 20191226 2019-12-18T05-41-37.9 2458835.74473 RV -1.586 0.202 Teff 6555 logg 4.09 feh -0.09 vsini 27.2). Gaia DR2 RV good enough to confirm cluster membership. But cluster membership and signal look v good -- this one is worth the effort! NB. sector 8 data are available. Nbhd reanalysis also v good. RVs solid enough. d=294pc. Rstar=1.5, Teff=6750K (lower from CHIRON Teff). Ziegler got speckle AO, rules out binary companion to ~0.2-0.3 arcsec.

name: Vela_OB2,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop7,Vela_OB2,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop7
pending_spectroscopic_observations: need recon spectrum (desparately, for Rstar and Rp measurement). If good, 7 RVs with PFS could show planetary.
pending_photometry_observations: hold off on g’ or b’ until get recon spectrm.
comment: CHAT (1, IBE). LCOGT (2, BEO, 2 OIBEO iband good). SG1 (Don Radford) 1 OIBEO (iband). V-shaped. Noisy star, 3% dip, PMS M dwarf. TESS data has at least s7+s9. Initially was just Zari+18 PMS, sector 9 boosted to CG19 VelaOB2 + Kounkel19 VelaOB2. CDIPS LCs exist for S7,S8,S9. 20200112: some b or g’-band totals might be nice, otherwise no more photometry needed. Need recon spectrum to determine Rstar better (or else use other method?), and thereby determine if possible planet, or not! (Rp is large). Note E(Bp-Rp)=1.37. 7 RVs could show planetary mass (e.g., HATS-71). TripleSpec4.1 recon spectrrum would be nice.

name: NGC 2546
comment: 20191209: LGB retiring due to unconvincing neighborhood, + weakly suspect depth increase in new S8 data.  Suspect occ depth. Candidate HJ in NGC 2546 (~150 Myr).  TESS S7+S8 available. Astrometric excess indicates likely presence of wide binary companion. RVs to rule out stellar EB needed! Cluster membership looks passable (it's Dias). Nbhd analysis indicates target is maybe 2 sigma away from expected cluster PM dispersion. It is also weakly in the foreground (maybe 1.5-2 sigma). It would be on the periphery of the cluster -- the neighborhood is not convincing.  If it's 150 Myr, where is the rotation signal?  Needs RVs to check for Li.  Worth continuing observations, but difficult to confirm. Teff~=6000K from Gaia Bp-Rp color + TICv8 spline relation, and is flagged as dwarf (TICv8 did not report stellar params, probably b/c of ~1 arcsec companion, deltaMag=2 Gaia DR2 5541111035708733056).

name: Collinder_135,cg19velaOB2_pop4,N/A,Collinder_135,cg19velaOB2_pop4,N/A
comment: M-dwarf + HJ/BD/M dwarf. 40 Myr old, Gaia membership is strong. 2.5Rjup radius is standard (see Burrows+2001 cooling track). TESS photometry shows rstar rotation is decoupled from orbital period. Need mass measurement to characterize system -- worth spending some time on. Nbhd analysis shows RA/dec a few deg from Collinder135 center. RV not available. PM good. Plx good. CMD good (pre-MS).

name: NGC_2527,NGC_2527
comment: Priority for RVs. LCOGT(4 useable from  20191215 & 20191217 & 20191224 & 20191229-- consistent, with shallow signals, but not particularly helpful b/c 0.2% dip). Possible super-Neptune, P=1.1 d orbit. CDIPS report centroid analysis not great b/c of crowdedness ...LCO  ground-based photometry (0.2% dip) did help rule out <40” NEB blends though. Nbhd analysis shows in RA/dec it's relatively far from cluster core (2-3 sigma). Plx, PM look great. CMD shows it's a little bit (1-2 sigma) faint. RA/dec space looks like ~2-3 sigma away from cluster center. CG18 Pmemb=90%. CHIRON(1 recon spectrum in fiber mode) shows star RV is consistent with Gaia cluster RV. Li is strong (as expected for Teff=6270K). 2019-11-26, RV 38.348 0.039 Teff 6236 logg 4.32 feh 0.17 vsini 12.0. Shows a "nice broad Li line".  vsini of 12km/s for a Teff=6270K star with Rstar between 1.14Rsun (TIC8) and ~1.3Rsun (Mamajek)implies Prot of ~4.5-5 days, consistent w/ Curtis’ gyro sequences of ~600Myr-1Gyr, and inconsistent with the Prot=10days seen in the field.

name: Haffner_13
comment: LCOGT(2, egresses). HATS (many G602/3, showed event seems to be off-target). Cand HJ around ~30 Myr star, strong rot variability.  Membership seems pretty good (CG18), but RV to verify couldn't hurt. Centriod looks good, but medium-crowded -- ground-based transit followup also needed. Nbhd analysis shows PMs maybe 1 sigma off. Plx good, position fine, CMD good.

name: ASCC_39
comment: 20191209: LGB retiring due to unconvincing existence of cluster (as visible in neighborhood plots). Cand HJ about K dwarf in ASCC 39. CG18 didnt recover this cluster (raises doubts about existence). Nor did Conrad+17. Cluster would need to be better characterized for strong claims to proceed. Nbhd analysis suggests cluster is maybe coherent in PM and parallax space... but even if it is, the star's membership in the cluster is tenuous. Can follow-up, would be hard to publish.

name: NGC_2421
comment: Phil Evans ruled out 21 ppt event on target, confirmed 200 ppt NEB on neighbor 7" East (w/ a 3" aperture). --> It's a NEB. LCOGT(2, 1 ambig, other ?).  Cand ultra-HJ on 16hr orbit around evolving(?) star in a ~40 Myr old cluster, at ~2kpc. Either (a) stellar EB, given dip size, or (b) inflated/still contracting giant planet / BD. Probably (a), but this one is worth checking. Nbhd analysis shows PMs good, parallax good, CMD is slightly turning off, position fine (maybe 1 sigma from center).

comment: Possible HJ in IC2602; likely EB; 2x TLS period.
Odd-even affected by spot detrending. Cand HJ, PMS K dwarf (Zari+18). Multisector (S9-S11).

name: Johansson_1
comment: Probable EB. Cand HJ in "Johansson 1" (maybe nonexistent, but stars more coeval than nbhd).

name: ASCC 24
comment: Candidate 30 Myr massive star with giant planet. Kinematics and phot plausible with cluster membership, but ASCC 24 is sparse, and K13 labels a MG.  However CG18 does not recover -- raises suspicions about the existence of the group itself.  Photometry would be surprisingly quiet for a 30 Myr star.  Need RV to check for consistency with Kharchenko+13 RV. Otherwise, further analysis of the group's existence is needed.

name: Bochum 5
comment: Phase modulation strongly suggests short-period eccentric EB.

name: Basel_11A
comment: Low SNR & crowded. Needs ground-based transits to confirm presence of signal, and location. Purported 2% signal, 50 Myr-old.

name: NGC_2548,NGC_2548,NGC2548
comment: Good SNR signal, V-shaped. SG2 lists: "V-shaped; Large planet; but could be close to 2 R_Jup. WASP follow-up shows this is a low-mass EB." CG18 P_memb = 100%, thuogh the LAMOST RV suggests otherwise (at low significance?). In M48, 400 Myr. Worth including in any homogeneous paper.

name: FSR_1077
comment: Tdur somewhat long, but good signal. CG18 doesn't recover FSR 1077 cluster (but it's an IR cluster). Froebrich+07 called it a "probable" cluster, rather than a "possible" one. However they raise a quality flag indicating that the contrast of the central to background star density is low. So basically: the cluster's existence still needs to be confirmed (or refuted) thru joint DR2 5dims + 2MASS photometry. Because based on optical data alone, its existence is not clear. Nbhd analysis shows Gaia PM and parallax don't cohere into any meaningful clump. This "cluster" is probably not real.

name: ASCC 35
comment: Outskirts of ASCC 35. Good signal (+weak spot modulation). CG18 didn't recover cluster, and no cluster RV available -> priority 1 instead of 0. Nbhd analysis shows: this cluster is just not at all apparent. Probably doesn't exist. (Downgraded furhter).

name: Platais 6
comment: Phase modulation-> EB.

name: Berkeley_28
comment: Cand young (~50 Myr) massive star w/ giant planet. Somewhat V-shaped. Proper motions suggest members in cluster outskirts. RV needed to confirm 6d position+velocity agree with cluster association. NB. strong spot modulation supports youth. Nbhd analysis shows PMs are just WAY OFF.

name: Collinder 70,--,Collinder 70,--
comment: Hot star, cluster outskirts, pulsation variability. Star is HD 37173, Houk+1999 classified as B6 II, with what they reported as a high-quality spectrum --> expected Rstar is 6Rsun. Dip is 0.5%. If SpType is correct, almost certainly stellar.

name: Collinder 70
comment: Good signal, questionable parallax (i.e. maybe not cluster member). Star is also not photometrically active enough for how young it's supposed to be. Possible OOT ellipsoidal phase variation. Only RV for cluster membership -- stellar mass EBs to be ruled out after. Nbhd analysis shows definitely not member (but that Collinder 70 is obviously real).

name: NGC_2516
comment: TLS double period. P~4 day HJ cand in NGC 2516. Multiple sector data available -> would benefit from analysis. Nbhd analysis shows that parallax is a bit small. Proper motions seem quite off. RV to confirm it's in the cluster would be needed... or to confirm youth. Weak membership. CHIRON (1, Zhou) shows double-peaked CCF, no signs of Li.

name: Gulliver_36
comment: Poss off-target, but WCS suspect (pg6) --> would need to be reanalyzed in a separate pipeline run.
Candidate PMS M-dwarf + HJ/BD/M dwarf.  BLS 2x period shows better OOT phase-modulation fit --> likely EB.

name: Collinder 132
comment: Raw LC OOT variations suspect --> either an EB, or a WASP-18 like HJ.  Parallax and photometry fine for cluster membership, but the proper motion is bad, indicating likely field contami--t. --theless, v nice signal. One or two RVs needed to confirm not cluster member. Don't follow for mass measurement until clarified. Nbhd analysis shows (a) the CG18 cluster members seem wrong.  The clump in proper motion space for Collinder 132 is different from where the members are. (b) From the PMs star is no way in either of the clumps.

name: NGC_2354
comment: Cand HJ in NGC 2354, a 300 Myr cluster. Note = HATS554-051.  Joel Hartman writes: "We have two egresses from the LCOGT 1m network, and an ingress observed by CHAT. We have 9 FEROS observations and 6 HARPS observations that show a fair amount of scatter, and do not phase up with the photometric ephemeris (we get a best-fit orbit of K = 100 +- 40 m/s). Probably this is due to the rapid rotation of the star. We have this marked as being in need of photometric follow-up in another band-pass, photometric follow-up covering a secondary eclipse, and blend analysis." TESS data enables all.  For cluster membership, Kharchenko gives Ps|Pkin|PJKs|PJH as  1|80.44|73.95|94.64.  The ~30-31km/s from the WiFeS/HARPS/FEROS RVs seem pretty consistent with the star being a cluster member.  Metallicity is also fine.  NB only 1 sector of TESS data available.  This is probably ready to publish, after a detailed blend analysis. However, a detailed manual analysis of the stars in the neighborhood by LGB showed that the parallax and proper motions are inconsistent with cluster membership -- the star is a foreground star.  In addition, the MS turnoff of the cluster is like ~2Msun, while this star is ~1.4Msun. Shy of any spectroscopic indications of stellar youth (e.g., Li? Halpha?), the cluster membership claim should be treated with heavy skepticism.
TOI 1098 in Octans, identified by Andrew Mann. P=10d, Rp=3.5Re, shallow. Rotn period good. Teff=6150K, T=8.7 (bright!). S12+13. Good RV target.

name: kc19group_64,--,kc19group_64,--
comment: TOI 1227 in Eps Cha, identified by Andrew Mann. P=27d, Rp=16Re, deep (M dwarf, V=17, T=13.8). S11+12, only 2 dips seen. Need phot followup.

name: ASCC_127,RSG_7,--,ASCC_127,RSG_7,--
comment: TOI 1497 in RSG_7 (200Myr), identified by Jerome de Leon. Rp=4Re, P=0.82d USP around V=10 hot star. 0.5mmag transits, but maybe worth clearing field of NEBs for validation. TRES (1, Bieryla) shows Vrot~120km/s, no chance at mass measurement. RM still possible?

TIC 166527623 in Sco Cen (Andrew Mann). SPOC S11 report shows strong rotation & dips; TOI process totally missed this one. Period & radius require manual insert. Was not on CDIPS target list, so missed even though LC was made. (T=9.2! So easy followup).
